fields.draw_shape_text:
Getting Started

Take the time to learn how to use this drawing tool before you dive in. The instructions and videos provided will quickly show you through the entire process

How It Works

The way the drawing process works is for each species group you target, you are given an imaginary bag of 100 pennies. You will draw shapes on the map representing your fishing grounds and then place some number of pennies on those shapes. The more pennies you place on a shape, the more value or importance you are placing on it. Keep doing this until you have drawn all your shapes and used all your pennies. This process may seem complicated but it will allow the potential impact of MPA's on each fishery and each region to be measured much more accurately.

How many shapes you draw and how specific you are is up to you. Most people draw between three and eight shapes per fishery per user group.

More Help

To get this window back after closing it, click the Help button in the upper right. Additional help can be found on our frequently asked questions page. Please do not hesitate to email fish@ecotrust.org if you need more help.


    Highly Recommended
fields.group_status_text:
Please carefully read all instructions and complete each survey section. You will be asked to answer questions and draw your fishing grounds. The drawing portion can be technically challenging and you may get discouraged by the amount of time it will take you. We apologize for this. Please understand that your input provides the best representation of your fishing interests and provides an opportunity for your voice to be heard. For these reasons, we believe the time you spend will be worth the effort.

If you have questions about Ecotrust's involvement in the MLPA process and what your incentive is to share your information and fishing grounds to us, please visit our MLPA page.

We are listening to your feedback. If you have technical problems please read our Frequently Asked Questions. If you are finding the online interview too difficult to complete, please email us at fish@ecotrust.org or call us using the number provided in your registration email. We are listening to your feedback.

Instructions

Complete each section below one at a time. A red circle indicates an unfinished section. Once you have completed the necessary steps within a section you will be able to finalize it. Once a group is finalized it will change to the color green. Once all groups are green you will be able to finalize your survey. You must complete at least the first user group including drawing your fishing grounds. You may skip the others and move on.
fields.assign_groups_text:
What percentage of time do you spend fishing in each of these user groups?

[Note: You won't be surveyed for groups you don't provide a value for here. Also these values must add up to 100%. For example, if someone participates in both kayak angling and dive angling, they might enter 60% for kayak angling, 40% for dive angling and nothing for private vessel angling.]
fields.interview_complete_text:
The fishing grounds you drew will be edited if necessary, using any bounding information you provided (e.g. north, south, east, and west boundaries). Our team will then begin the process of aggregating the surveys to create maps showing overall fishing grounds and their value for different user-group/fishery/port combinations.

When the initial round of analysis is complete we will conduct reviews by port group. This will provide an opportunity for groups of fishermen to give feedback on the accuracy of the regional data. Again, this will be done in such a way that your individual fishing grounds will not be identifiable. Recommendations from the review meetings will be incorporated and subsequent iterations of the analysis will be completed. The maps will then be used in evaluating MPA proposals. For each MPA proposal, stakeholders will be able to see the potential impacts that MPA would have on a given fishery and/or user group. This is a valuable tool in finding the best areas for protection while trying to minimize the impact on fisheries.

Your willingness to participate is greatly appreciated! If you have any questions or concerns please contact us at fish@ecotrust.org

Instructions

Complete each section below one at a time. You will be asked to finalize each section before moving onto the next. You can logout of the survey at any time and your survey will be saved for you to finish at a later time.

We strongly encourage feedback. If you have technical problems please read our Frequently Asked Questions. If you are finding the online interview too difficult to complete, or have additional questions, please email us at fish@ecotrust.org and we will respond within a few hours if not sooner.
fields.assign_groups_text:
Please carefully read all instructions and complete each survey section. You will be asked to answer questions on fishing trip expenditures and draw your fishing grounds for each species you target.

We greatly appreciate your participation as your direct input provides the best representation of your fishing interests and provides an opportunity for your voice to be heard. For these reasons, we believe the time you spend in this survey will be worth the effort.

First, what percentage of time do you spend fishing in each of the following user groups? [These values must add up to 100%. For example, 60% for kayak fishing, 40% for sport boat fishing.]
fields.interview_complete_text:
The fishing grounds you drew will be edited if necessary, using any bounding information you provided (e.g. north, south, east, and west boundaries). Our team will then begin the process of aggregating the surveys to create maps showing overall fishing grounds and their value for different user-group/fishery/port combinations.

When the initial round of analysis is complete we will conduct reviews by port group. This will provide an opportunity for groups of fishermen to give feedback on the accuracy of the regional data. Again, this will be done in such a way that your individual fishing grounds will not be identifiable. Recommendations from the review meetings will be incorporated to complete the maps. The maps will then be submitted to Oregon’s Department of Land and Conservation Development to be considered along with other data and information to help guide the location of waver energy sites so that impacts to existing uses are minimized.

Your willingness to participate is greatly appreciated! If you have any questions or concerns please contact us at fish@ecotrust.org

fields.answer: We understand that water temperature and other factors affect migratory patterns of species like tuna.  This will make the general area you fish larger when looking at things all together like this but often there are still specific places you fish.  Maybe certain sections of water always tend to be warmer and you tend to do better there.  Maybe you don't fish tuna unless they're within 20 miles of shore or maybe you do multi-days out 60 miles.  Maybe you don't fish tuna any further north or south than a given point.  That's the information we want to capture.
fields.question: I don't fish in the same places for migratory fish like tuna.  How do I deal with that when drawing fishing grounds?

fields.answer: The map takes the longest to load.  People without a broadband internet connection may need to wait up to a minute or two the first time they draw fishing grounds.  If you wait and still nothing loads then try refreshing the page. If still nothing then verify you are using a supported browser (IE 6+, Firefox 1.0+, Safari 1.2+, Chrome 2+). If you have a supported browser then next verify you have 'javascript' enabled in your browser preferences (it is by default). Seek the help of friends and family if you're unsure how to do any of these steps or email us at fish@ecotrust.org.  Another option is simply to try another computer. Computers more than 5 years old are more likely to have issues.
fields.question: Why is the page not loading correctly or not loading at all when I go to draw fishing grounds?

fields.answer:
The precision of your fishing grounds is important; however, we understand that accuracy will vary between users.  Please just do the best you can with the time you have and provide us with any extra information on boundaries so that our team can make your fishing grounds more accurate.

We also understand that you might be reluctant to share your favorite little fishing hole, while at the same time you don't want to lose it.  Just make sure your fishing hole is at least captured in one of your fishing grounds and you put a sufficient value on it.

In most cases you should not be drawing a single fishing ground that covers hundreds of square miles.  Tuna and other migratory species are a bit of an exception.  Split these large fishing grounds up into multiple areas if possible and weight them separately with pennies.
fields.question: How much precision should I use when drawing fishing grounds?

fields.answer: The information you provide will be used to represent the socioeconomic importance of recreational fishing areas along the coast of Oregon. This information will help guide the placement of wave energy facilities in ways that reduce the impacts on fishermen. By taking part in this survey, you have the opportunity to directly contribute to Oregon’s wave energy planning process and enable decision-makers to reduce potential impacts on fishermen and the coastal economies.
fields.question: Why should I provide information about my fishing?

fields.answer: No, Ecotrust’s Oregon Fisheries Uses and Values project was designed and began as a solely state funded project. This project from the beginning has been designed to respond and address the fishing community’s need to be represented alongside other datasets in Oregon’s Territorial Sea Planning process. Packard will not receive any data from Ecotrust nor do they have input or influence on how the project is conducted. Packard has simply provided the funds up front for a project that had already been conceptualized with the state and the fishing community.
fields.question: Does the Packard Foundation have control over any aspect of the project or the data collected?

fields.answer: The data collected on recreational, charter, and commercial fishing grounds will be aggregated (all individual information combined) to create ‘heat maps’ for each fishery-sector combination in each port. These ‘heat maps’ will display the relative importance of fishing grounds, with red hot areas indicating areas of high importance. How maps are presented to the DLCD for planning usage will be at the discretion of each port’s fishing community. A community may decide to release individual fishery-sector maps or they may simply release what we call a ‘cross-sector aggregate map’ which gives equal weight to and combines each sector’s (recreational, charter, and commercial) grounds into one map. This type of map was created and released for the Southern Oregon Ocean Resources Coalition (SOORC) and has set the standard for what at minimum the state will accept for the Territorial Sea Planning process. This type of map will also be the method to display the relative importance of fishing grounds in a state-wide map.
fields.question: How will fishing area information be used?

fields.answer: The data collected on fishing expenditures will be used to conduct economic impact analyses on candidate wave energy locations. These impact analyses will not only calculate the potential loss of revenue and percentage loss of fishing grounds to the commercial, charter, and recreational sectors but also to the adjacent coastal and state economies- which fishermen have long called attention to the importance of representing. It should be emphasized that this survey is not designed to determine the overall value of recreational, charter, or commercial fishing in a particular port or to the overall state/coastal economy. Moreover, summary statistics on economic information provided will not be compiled of made public. The expenditure survey is solely designed to determine the general percentage of expenditures associated with the various industries that also rely upon fishing.
fields.question: How will economic information be used?

fields.answer: Ecotrust will widely announce and hold review map meetings with the fishing community in each port. These fishermen will then provide feedback to ensure the data collected is an accurate representation of the relative importance of fishing grounds associated with their port. During the review map meeting each sector (commercial, charter, and recreational) will be provided individual fishery and aggregate maps to review. These maps are only for review purpose and will not be released to any individual or group. During the Oregon Territorial Sea Planning process Ecoturst will also work with fishing communities and association to review impact analyses on identified potential waver energy sites.
fields.question: How will you check the accuracy of fishing ground maps and information?

fields.answer: All individual information will be kept private and confidential. The only information that is made public are the maps that each port fishing communities decides to submit to the DLCD- such as the cross-sector aggregate maps (mentioned in the “How will fishing area information be used?” question above).
fields.question: What information is kept private and what is public?

fields.answer: The Department of Land Conservation and Development (DLCD) will be administering the planning process which will involve Oregon’s Ocean Policy Advisory Council (OPAC) and Territorial Sea Plan Advisory Committee (TSPAC). These entities have several fishing interests serving in these groups. Decision-making and planning will be done on a port by port scale with input from various stakeholders including the fishing community at every step.  However, the entity responsible for approving a TSP plan under Oregon Law is the Land Conservation and Development Commission (LCDC) which will receive recommendations from the DLCD based on the community input outlined above.
fields.question: Who is in charge of Oregon’s Territorial Sea planning process and who will be making decisions?

fields.answer: Only the cross-sector aggregate maps are made public and requests for this information must be made through the DLCD. Any other requests for more detailed information belongs to the decision of each fishing community and their representatives, such as; SOORC (Southern Oregon Ocean Resource Coalition), FINE (Fishermen Involved in Natural Energy), FACT (Fisherman Advisory Committee of Tillamook), and NSAT (Depoe Bay Near Shore Action Team). If these groups decide it is to the benefit of the fishing community to release additional data (such as sector or species maps) then each individual fisherman that contributed information to the maps must be contacted and approve its use for the solicited purpose. However, under no circumstances will individual information be released.
fields.question: Can individuals or institutions/agencies ask permission to see additional information? Who will control the release of that information?
